# ACT 3 - Scene 13: Scar and Steady (Empathy Path)
# File: a3_s13_scar_and_steady_emp.rpy
# Type: TESSA FIRST EROTIC
# =======================================================

# ========= SCENE START TASKS =========
$ _current_scene_id = "a3_s13_scar_and_steady_emp"
$ scene_mark(_current_scene_id, "entered")

label a3_s13_scar_and_steady_emp:


    # Gallery — unlock this scene in the character replay grid.
    $ gallery_unlock("a3_s13_scar_and_steady_emp")
    $ show_timeline("DAY 38", "22:00", "Phoenix Base — Medbay")
    # ========= STAGE DIRECTIONS (cinema-first) =========
    # CAMERA: 50mm, handheld with minimal drift (2-3%). Opens on Tessa's hands —
    #         filling the frame, clinical, precise. Slowly widens to include Aeron.
    #         The camera follows Tessa's hands for the first half — her hands are the
    #         protagonist until the scene shifts. After the Brand scar beat: the camera
    #         finds faces. Close singles. Eye-level. No angles — equality.
    # LIGHTING: Medbay — overhead surgical strips (5600K harsh) directly above the
    #           treatment station. Periphery warm (amber practicals, 2800K). As the scene
    #           shifts from clinical to intimate, Tessa dims the overheads. The amber
    #           takes over. The light softens as the pretense does.
    # SFX: Loop — medbay ambient: ventilation, generator hum, distant base activity.
    #       Fading as the scene narrows to the two of them.
    #       One-shots — antiseptic spray, bandage tear, scissors snip, metal tray,
    #       fabric rustle, breath catch, the quiet click of the overhead dimmer.
    # FX/COMP: The wound — a gash on Aeron's left forearm from the checkpoint scramble.
    #          Tessa's instruments: improvised but functional. Suture kit. Antiseptic.
    #          The Brand scar — visible when his sleeve is pushed up past the wound.
    #          Older. Deliberate. The geometry of institutional marking.
    # BLOCKING: Medbay treatment station. Tessa standing, Aeron seated on the examination
    #           bench. Close quarters. Her hands on his arm. The physical arrangement is
    #           medical; the tension is not.
    # CANON: MAJOR SCENE. Tessa first erotic. Callbacks: a2_s18 (The Patient — trembling
    #        hands, Tessa treating Noelle), a2_s23 (mercy death — hands steady for killing,
    #        shaking after). The Brand scar from Act 1. "Count the Living" as Tessa's
    #        evolving thesis.
    # FACE: Tessa — professional mask intact until the Brand scar. Then: something raw.
    #        Her hands are the emotional barometer — steady when she's in control,
    #        trembling when she's not, and for the first time: steady when she's honest.
    #        Aeron — vulnerable. Literally shirtsleeved. Being tended to instead of commanding.

    # ========= VOICE BASELINE =========
    # EMP cadence. Tessa drives — she's the one with her hands on him.
    # Her clinical language erodes gradually. The medical terminology gives way to
    # something direct, unadorned, real. Tessa doesn't dress things up.
    # Aeron is quieter. He's the patient. For once, he lets someone take care of him.

    # --- VISUAL SETUP ---
    # [INT. PHOENIX BASE - MEDBAY - NIGHT]
    # After the story-keeper revelation (s20) — Aeron has learned his
    # mother is alive. He's been carrying accumulated wounds from ops
    # for days. Tessa catches him.

    #scene bg_medbay_emp_night with dissolve
    #play ambient "sfx/ambient/medbay_quiet_night.ogg" fadein 2.0

    # ========== PHASE 1 — THE TREATMENT ==========

    "The medbay is empty. It has been empty for hours. The base is still processing the story-keeper revelation — everyone is either at the mapping station or trying to sleep."

    "Aeron is neither. Aeron is in the medbay because Tessa saw the blood on his sleeve during the briefing and said nothing until the room cleared."

    t "Sit."

    a "It's a scratch."

    t "Sit down."

    "He sits. Tessa is already at the instrument tray. Antiseptic. Suture kit. Gauze. The tools laid out in the order she'll use them — the same order every time."

    athought "She didn't ask what happened. She saw the blood on my sleeve during the debrief and waited until everyone else was gone."

    athought "Tessa treats people in order of severity. I'm last because my wound is least."

    athought "She also treats people in order of privacy. I'm last because this one requires rolling up my sleeve."

    "She pulls on gloves. Latex snap. Professional."

    t "Sleeve."

    "He pushes his left sleeve up past the elbow. The gash is on the outer forearm — a clean cut from a tunnel support strut during the Group Six scramble. It's already clotted."

    t "Liar. That's not a scratch."

    a "It's shallow."

    t "Three centimeters. Shallow but long. You need four sutures minimum."

    "She cleans the wound. Antiseptic on gauze, applied with the particular pressure of someone who knows exactly how much it stings and doesn't apologize for it."

    athought "Her hands are steady."

    athought "I've watched them shake. After the mercy death in the Sector 9 camp. After treating Dren's broken hands."

    athought "They shake when she's done. Never during."

    t "Hold still."

    "The suture needle. She threads it without looking — muscle memory deeper than conscious thought."

    "First suture. A sharp pinch, then the pull."

    t "One."

    "Second. He doesn't flinch."

    t "Two. You don't have to prove anything."

    a "I'm not proving anything."

    t "You tensed your jaw instead of flinching. That's performing stoicism, not experiencing painlessness."

    athought "She reads bodies the way Noelle reads data. There is no lying to Tessa's hands."

    "Third suture."

    t "Three. Almost done."

    "Fourth."

    t "Four."

    "She ties off the last stitch. Clips the thread. Reaches for the bandage."

    "And stops."

    # ========== PHASE 2 — THE BRAND ==========

    "His sleeve is pushed up past the wound. Past the sutures. Past the ordinary topography of forearm muscle and vein."

    "To the scar beneath."

    "The Brand. Glass Academy. The mark they put on every operative who completed the program — a geometric pattern seared into the inner forearm. Precise lines. Institutional geometry. Skin that was deliberately destroyed and allowed to heal wrong."

    athought "I forget about it most of the time. It's been there since I was seventeen."

    athought "I forget that other people don't forget."

    "Tessa's gloved fingers hover over it. Not touching. Reading."

    t "Second-degree burn pattern. Thermal application. Controlled depth — someone used a template."

    athought "Her voice is clinical. Her breathing isn't."

    t "The scarring suggests it was treated afterward. Not well, but treated. Enough to prevent infection."

    a "They treated all of them. Can't have operatives dying of wound sepsis during branding."

    "She looks up. Her eyes meet his."

    t "How old were you?"

    a "Seventeen."

    t "Voluntary?"

    a "In the sense that refusing would have ended my career, my housing, and my relationship with the only parent I had."

    "Tessa's jaw tightens. The clinical mask doesn't crack — it thins."

    t "That's not voluntary."

    a "I know that now."

    "Her fingers move. Cross the two centimeters of air between glove and scar."

    "She traces the Brand. One line. Then another."

    "Then she catches herself. Pulls her hand back."

    t "Sorry. I shouldn't—"

    a "It's okay."

    t "No. I should have asked."

    athought "She's right. And the fact that she caught herself — that she named the trespass before I felt it as one — says more about Tessa than any diagnosis she's ever given."

    a "You can. If you want to."

    "Her hand returns. Slower this time. Deliberate. Her thumb traces the outer edge of the Brand — the boundary between marked skin and unmarked."

    t "Does it still hurt?"

    a "Not physically."

    t "I know."

    athought "She does know. Her hands have mapped enough scars to read the ones that live underneath the skin."

    # ========== PHASE 3 — THE CONVERSATION ==========

    "She finishes the bandage. The gash is covered. The Brand is not."

    "Neither of them moves to push his sleeve down."

    t "Two hundred and six."

    a "You're counting."

    t "I always count. Count the living — that's the job."

    a "Is it still the job?"

    "She pulls off the gloves. Sets them on the tray. Her bare hands now — small, capable, still."

    t "I used to think counting the living was enough. Triage. Prioritize. Save who you can. Accept the math."

    t "Then I watched you thread two hundred people through a 47-second window in the dark."

    t "And I stood at the exit point treating scraped knees and sprained ankles. Fourteen minor injuries for two hundred people."

    t "That's not triage. That's something else."

    a "What is it?"

    t "It's care at scale. It's the thing I do one patient at a time, but you did it for two hundred."

    "She's looking at his arm. At the sutures over the Brand."

    t "I fix what's broken. You kept it from breaking."

    athought "She says it simply. The way she says everything — without ornamentation."

    athought "Tessa has never once told me something she didn't mean."

    t "The corridor operation. Group Six — the two-second margin."

    a "What about it?"

    t "You adjusted the entire operation in real time to keep twenty people safe. Including three children."

    t "You did the math that doesn't make them expendable."

    athought "She's echoing Kael's promise from the council. 'We protect everyone or this means nothing.'"

    athought "But coming from Tessa, it sounds different. Not idealism. Confirmation. A medic's verdict on a field commander."

    "She sits on the examination bench beside him. Not professional distance — personal distance."

    t "I've been thinking about the mercy death."

    "He doesn't need to ask which one."

    t "My hands were steady for it. Steady through it. Steady enough to do the one thing nobody else in that camp could do."

    t "And then they shook for forty minutes."

    a "I know."

    t "You stayed."

    a "Of course I stayed."

    t "Not 'of course.' Nothing about that was 'of course.' You could have given me space. You could have left it to Lyra."

    t "You stayed and you didn't say anything and you didn't try to fix it. You just waited until my hands stopped shaking."

    athought "I remember. The camp. The smoke. Her hands vibrating against her thighs like they were trying to discharge something electrical."

    athought "I sat beside her and I didn't speak."

    athought "Some things don't need words. They need witnesses."

    t "That mattered."

    a "Tessa—"

    t "Let me finish."

    "She looks at him. Her hands are in her lap. Bare. Still."

    t "I count the living because someone has to. Because the dead deserve to be subtracted with accuracy and the living deserve to be held with intention."

    t "You are living, Aeron. You are counted."

    athought "My name from her mouth sounds like a medical fact. Vital signs confirmed. Patient present."

    athought "Something in my chest cracks. Not breaks — cracks open."

    # ========== PHASE 4 — CONSENT GATES ==========

    "The medbay is quiet. The overhead strips buzz. The amber practicals glow at the edges."

    "Her hand is on his arm. Over the bandage. Over the sutures. Her thumb resting against the gauze."

    # CONSENT GATE A: Tessa's verbal cue (medical frame crossing into personal)

    t "I should check if the sutures are holding."

    "Her hand moves to the bandage edge. Lifts it slightly. Inspects."

    t "They're holding."

    "Her hand stays."

    athought "The sutures don't need checking. We both know that."

    athought "Her hand is on my arm and it has nothing to do with medicine anymore."

    # CONSENT GATE B: Aeron's reciprocal

    "He covers her hand with his."

    "Her fingers go still under his palm."

    athought "Her hands. The ones that shake after. The ones that are steady now."

    athought "I hold them the way she held the suture needle — with intention."

    "She looks at their hands. Then at him."

    t "That's not a medical intervention."

    a "No. It's not."

    # CONSENT GATE C: Explicit exit acknowledged

    t "If this crosses a line for you—"

    a "You ARE the line. The one I keep coming back to."

    "She stares at him. The clinical mask is gone. What's underneath is not fragile — it's exposed. The difference matters. Fragile things break. Exposed things are simply seen."

    t "That's the most reckless thing anyone's ever said to me."

    a "Is it wrong?"

    t "No. That's the problem."

    "She reaches for the overhead dimmer. Clicks it. The surgical white fades. The amber takes the room."

    "Her hand finds his jaw. The touch of someone who knows anatomy — where the nerve endings cluster, where the skin is thinnest, where a touch becomes a current."

    athought "Her hands are steady."

    athought "Mine are not."

    "She kisses him. Not tentative. Not testing. Direct. The way Tessa does everything — with complete commitment and zero pretense."

    athought "She tastes like field rations and antiseptic and something warm underneath — something that was always there, under the professionalism, under the steady hands."

    "He pulls her closer. She lets him. Shifts on the bench until they're facing each other, her knees bracketing his, her hands on his shoulders."

    t "Tell me if—"

    a "I will."

    t "I mean it."

    a "I know you do. So do I."

    athought "Her fingers find the hem of his shirt. Clinical knowledge repurposed — she knows exactly where the fabric ends and the skin begins."

    athought "Her hands are warm. Warmer than I expected."

    athought "I expected steady. I didn't expect warm."

    # [INTIMATE CONTENT HERE]

    # ========== PHASE 5 — AFTERCARE ==========

    # VISUAL: Later. The medbay. Amber light only. They're sitting on the examination bench,
    # backs against the wall. Her head on his shoulder. His bandaged arm across her lap.
    # Her fingers tracing the gauze absently.
    # CAMERA: Wide. Still. Holding the frame like a breath held gently.

    "The examination bench was not designed for two people. They make it work."

    "Her head on his shoulder. His arm across her lap — the bandaged one. Her fingers trace the gauze over the sutures. Not checking. Touching."

    athought "The medbay hums. The generator. The ventilation. The sounds of a building that keeps going."

    athought "We keep going. That's the revelation. Not that we survived the corridor operation. That we're here, afterward, and the world didn't stop."

    "She lifts her head."

    t "I'm going to name what just happened."

    a "I wouldn't expect anything less."

    t "That was me choosing someone."

    "Not 'falling for.' Not 'giving in to.' Choosing."

    t "I've spent three years keeping everyone else alive. Counting the living. Setting bones and closing wounds and watching my hands shake afterward."

    t "I chose you because you're the first person who made me think the counting might include me."

    athought "She says it flat. No poetry. No ceremony."

    athought "Tessa names things because unnamed things fester. That's the medic in her."

    athought "The woman in her just told me I matter. In the most Tessa way possible."

    a "You're counted, Tessa. You always were."

    t "Shut up. I'm not done."

    "He waits."

    t "You're still here."

    a "Yeah."

    t "After the corridor. After two hundred people. After the two-second margin and the Group Six adjustment and the entire operation running on your father's playbook turned inside out."

    t "You're still here. In my medbay. Letting me stitch you up."

    t "That's the thing, Aeron. You're still here."

    athought "Three words. The diagnosis underneath every other diagnosis."

    athought "Still here. Present. Counted among the living."

    "Her hands are in her lap. She looks at them."

    "They're steady."

    "She watches them for a long moment. Turns them over. Flexes the fingers."

    t "Huh."

    a "What?"

    t "They're not shaking."

    "She holds them up. Steady. Level. The medbay light catching the lines of her palms."

    t "After the mercy death, they shook for forty minutes. After Dren's hands, twenty. After every surgery, every triage, every time I do the hard thing and come out the other side."

    t "They always shake after."

    "She looks at him."

    t "Not tonight."

    athought "Not tonight."

    athought "For the first time, Tessa's hands are steady after."

    athought "I don't know what that means. I think she does."

    athought "I think it means she found the thing that stops the tremor."

    athought "Not a cure. A counterweight."

    "She puts her hand on his chest. Over his heart. The medic's gesture — checking pulse."

    "But she doesn't count the beats."

    "She just listens."

    #stop ambient fadeout 3.0
    #scene black with fade

    # ========= STATE UPDATES =========
    $ rel_bump("Tessa", trust=2, affection=2)
    $ flag("tessa_first_intimate", True)
    $ metric("tessa_intimacy_level", set_to=max(metric("tessa_intimacy_level"), 1))
    $ npc_remember("Tessa", "first_intimate_medbay", tone="grounded_warmth")
    $ npc_remember("Tessa", "hands_steady_after", tone="quiet_revelation")
    $ npc_remember("Tessa", "saw_brand_scar", tone="controlled_grief")
    $ scene_mark(_current_scene_id, "completed")

    return


